# Cloudflare Pages cache headers.
#
# Lives outside client/public/ so GitHub Pages (preview) does not serve this
# file at /_headers — it is consumed only by the production Cloudflare Pages
# deploy, which copies it into the dist/ root before `pages deploy`. See
# .github/workflows/release.yml (deploy-production job).
#
# Strategy:
# - Service worker, registration shim, manifest, and entry HTML MUST revalidate
#   every request. They are the entry points that decide which bundle the user
#   ends up on; if a stale copy is served from the edge or browser cache the
#   user is stuck on the old version until the cache TTL expires, requiring a
#   manual hard refresh to unstick. `max-age=0, must-revalidate` forces a
#   conditional GET (fast 304 in the common case) without disabling caching.
# - Hashed assets under /assets/ are content-addressed (filename changes when
#   content changes), so they are safe to cache forever. `immutable` tells the
#   browser to skip revalidation entirely — even on reload — which both
#   tightens the post-deploy story (no chance of mixed-version assets sneaking
#   through) and reduces request volume.
#
# When a new entry-point file is added (e.g. a new top-level worker script),
# add its path here too.

/sw.js
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate

/registerSW.js
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate

/manifest.webmanifest
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate

/workbox-*.js
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate

/index.html
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate

/
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate

/assets/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
